WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.360
Welcome, everyone, to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:12.600
And I know most people who are on today, you've been here before, so you kind of know the

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:13.600
drill.

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:19.000
But for anyone who's new today, this is an open space for current and aspiring data science

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.080
leaders to connect and just chat about some of the more human-centric questions around

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:29.320
data science leadership, but also to focus on questions that are most important to you

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:30.320
all.

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.880
So, there's three ways that you can ask questions.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:40.080
You could just jump in live, put questions in the chat, or we also do have a Slido link

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:44.320
where you can ask anonymous questions, too.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:51.060
And Rob will share that link in the chat in just a moment here.

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:57.759
But just a quick note that this session will be recorded and shared up to YouTube, so just

00:00:57.759 --> 00:01:00.360
want to make you aware of that if you're jumping in live.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:05.040
But again, feel free to ask questions anonymously, too.

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:10.839
I'm so happy to be joined by my co-host for today, Zac Garland, Manager of Econometrics

00:01:10.839 --> 00:01:13.839
and Data Science at Mastercard.

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:17.879
And Zac, I'd love to just have you introduce yourself and maybe share a bit about the work

00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:20.040
that you're doing on your team today.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:22.040
Yeah, no, absolutely.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:23.040
Hi, everyone.

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:26.360
My name is Zac Garland.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:30.120
I'm part of the Economics Institute at Mastercard.

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:38.440
And I think the easiest way to kind of summarize what we do, we like building cool shit.

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:44.959
And I'll try to not cuss, but I wanted to make this feel very open.

00:01:44.959 --> 00:01:50.080
I'm obviously not in a suit or anything special.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:53.760
I'm kind of in what I'm in every day.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:57.839
And so yeah, open questions, feel free to ask anything.

00:01:57.839 --> 00:02:01.599
Yeah, excited to be here.

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:02.599
Awesome.

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:08.479
So while we're waiting for a few questions to come in as well, Zac, I think one of the

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:15.559
things that was really interesting to me chatting with you this week is really about the ways

00:02:15.559 --> 00:02:22.720
that you make people interested in data and then the work that you're doing on your team.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:27.199
And I think it'd be cool to just maybe share a few examples of some of the stuff that you're

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:28.199
working on.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:32.080
Yeah, no, absolutely.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:39.240
So I guess there's a lot of broad things that data science covers.

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:45.320
I think that we try to figure out how to approach it really holistically.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:51.119
You know, from the point that you pull the data to transforming the data or visualizing

00:02:51.119 --> 00:02:54.839
it and I guess some simple plots.

00:02:54.839 --> 00:03:01.160
And then how does that eventually make its way to either a product or an output like

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:02.520
a report?

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:08.199
So one of the ways that we're constantly communicating is really a public report.

00:03:08.199 --> 00:03:14.559
And then we have kind of our client presentations or I guess you could say stakeholder presentations

00:03:14.559 --> 00:03:18.039
where that's really the summarized view.

00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:25.119
In general, I mean, I think that we always try to summarize big topics in a way that

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:26.199
everyone can consume.

00:03:26.199 --> 00:03:29.399
And that's my dog, Winston, by the way, for anyone that was curious.

00:03:29.399 --> 00:03:32.600
I love the dog running up in the background.

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:36.000
Yeah, no, he's the big one homie.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:44.000
But yeah, and I think that we try to find ways to explain it to a sixth grader, right?

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:50.080
I think within data science, you can get very, very in the weeds and it's all super exciting

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:52.360
for people that understand it.

00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:58.080
But for someone that's not familiar with data science or how to interpret data, you almost

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:05.160
have to find a way to really explain it or find a way to summarize your ideas.

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.960
And so I think that that's always been kind of a driving factor for us.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:19.359
And even we have this framework where it's what am I looking at and why does it matter?

00:04:19.359 --> 00:04:23.320
And it's two very simple questions.

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:29.920
But I think it gets to the heart of what you're trying to do, which is show something and

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:31.440
then why does that matter?

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:35.519
And so, yeah, that's kind of a side comment, but...

00:04:36.519 --> 00:04:37.519
Awesome.

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:44.640
And kind of going on that path as well, I see, Kevin, you just asked a question around

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:49.519
the what's your latest fun project that you've worked on?

00:04:49.519 --> 00:04:58.000
Yeah, so I would say that it was a very fun project, but it was very, very work intensive.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.559
So we're coming out with a small business report and the fun thing, at least from my

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:12.880
perspective, I like developing, I like code, and I've been learning JavaScript, trying

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:14.799
to find more ways to use it.

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:19.839
And so from my perspective, the most exciting or fun thing was I finally found a way to

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:29.760
have basically a static rendered R Markdown map show all of these individual city level

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.839
leaflet maps.

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:36.320
And so I'm talking in R, but I think that's probably acceptable here.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:43.119
But it was super fun for me to figure that out and find a way to make it work.

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:46.880
And yeah, I think it's a very visually appealing report.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:54.079
And so I think we're releasing it next Tuesday, and I can send out a link to that.

00:05:54.799 --> 00:06:02.399
There is just a general MasterCard services.com slash Economics Institute, where you can find

00:06:02.399 --> 00:06:04.079
like most of our public reports.

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:09.040
And so that's a really good place that we kind of see what's accessible or out in the

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:10.640
public view.

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:17.040
And then outside of that, I would say that we're constantly trying to focus on the business

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:20.399
or trying to understand where does this fit in the big picture?

00:06:21.359 --> 00:06:24.239
How do we provide value to our clients?

00:06:24.239 --> 00:06:26.160
How do we provide value to our stakeholders?

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:29.519
And so those are always really exciting.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:36.480
Those are more thought processes or how do we think about this?

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:38.959
How do we think about it differently?

00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:39.679
What's bad?

00:06:39.679 --> 00:06:40.239
What's good?

00:06:40.799 --> 00:06:41.600
So on and so forth.

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:43.200
So yeah.

00:06:44.959 --> 00:06:51.119
One question that I had for you, and if anybody else has other questions you want to ask live,

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:52.160
feel free to jump in.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:07:00.559
But I know MasterCard being such a huge company, I was curious how you go about like showing

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:07.359
the value of open source and explaining to maybe other stakeholders the importance of

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:08.000
open source?

00:07:08.959 --> 00:07:10.160
Yeah, no, absolutely.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:16.480
So I think when I think about open source, I mean, I'm in love with open source.

00:07:17.679 --> 00:07:26.000
I think there's a lot of value in sharing code and using code, debugging code, and having

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:26.880
that all available.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:34.399
And so I mean, one of the reasons why I'm such a RStudio supporter or advocate is all

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:40.559
of the packages were built for some reason, and they all more or less speak together.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:42.559
They talk to each other.

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:47.519
They have the ability to integrate functions with one another.

00:07:47.519 --> 00:07:55.519
And I think when you start to scratch, which is really what I joined shortly after the

00:07:55.519 --> 00:08:02.880
group was started, and there wasn't any paved pathway or any determined, this is what we

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:03.440
have to do.

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:11.600
And so when you start from scratch like that, it offers the ability to really design a full

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:19.279
framework or a entire system or entire portal, however you want to kind of describe it.

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:25.359
But it makes it interesting when you start doing that to see how much you're leveraging

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:28.399
open source, because it's probably a lot.

00:08:29.359 --> 00:08:36.159
And that's always been kind of my view that many companies are seeing the end result of

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:37.280
open source.

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:44.479
But I think the conversation really has started to turn more towards how do we start to be

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:45.359
an active member?

00:08:46.559 --> 00:08:56.960
How do we start to think about what we need to keep very secure and I guess behind some

00:08:56.960 --> 00:08:58.400
form of authentication?

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:03.440
And then how do we also start to generate new ideas with open source?

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:07.119
Or how do we start to partner with them to take on a big project?

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:13.599
Or if we have an idea, how do we start to think about what can be open source versus

00:09:13.599 --> 00:09:14.320
what couldn't be?

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:19.200
And I think the easiest intro to that is talking through inner source.

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:21.679
So how do we share within the company first?

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:29.359
And how do we start to approach, you know, broad frameworks or, you know, building out

00:09:29.359 --> 00:09:30.960
all of these different components?

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:37.760
And so I think the inner source conversation is an easier one to approach or get into.

00:09:38.719 --> 00:09:44.320
But I think eventually that really transitions into how do we talk about open source?

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:46.479
How do we, you know, view open source?

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:49.760
And how do we really collaborate and contribute?

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:58.159
That's one of the first times I myself have heard the like inner source and open source

00:09:58.159 --> 00:10:04.159
conversation and was just curious if others from the group as well have talked about it

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:06.799
that way or thought about it that way with leadership.

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:17.919
We've talked about it and implemented certain things, but I like having the term that

00:10:17.919 --> 00:10:20.640
specifically identifies what you're saying.

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:22.080
I'm going to totally take your term.

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:24.320
Sure.

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:25.760
What is worth is not my term.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:29.280
I don't remember where I read it, but I was like, yes, that's exactly it.

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:32.260
Yeah.

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:35.359
I'm trying to thank you for sharing it.

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:36.479
Of course.

00:10:38.239 --> 00:10:38.880
I like that.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.239
Daniel, I see that you asked the question in the chat and wanted to pass the mic over

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:45.760
to you to have you ask that live.

00:10:47.119 --> 00:10:47.840
Sure, sure.

00:10:48.799 --> 00:10:52.719
So basically, my question was just if you could talk a little bit about kind of like

00:10:52.719 --> 00:10:58.640
the idea generation and idea refinement process to kind of get to things that you actually

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:04.559
want your team to work on in the sense that like, I think a common dilemma is that like

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:06.400
the I just use business.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:09.280
It's kind of like the non-tech folks, but like the business folks kind of know a lot

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:13.359
about their individual problem areas, but don't know about the tech side and the tech

00:11:13.359 --> 00:11:15.840
side obviously knows the tech side, but not the business side.

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:22.719
And so you can get ideas from either or, but like how you go about kind of getting

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:27.919
this from the larger number of like potential projects to the ones that like you actually

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:29.039
have your team working on.

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:32.479
Yeah, no, I think that that's a great question.

00:11:34.239 --> 00:11:40.400
I would say that our team is constantly generating ideas.

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:50.000
And so I would say that we have a very almost open board when it comes to new ideas or doing

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:50.719
new things.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:58.640
And I think we're very quick to drop something that we thought was interesting, but then

00:11:59.599 --> 00:12:07.039
turns out it would take too much or the data would be too hard to pull, or there's something

00:12:07.039 --> 00:12:10.000
that causes us to kind of change paths.

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:15.520
And then when we find something that's really good, I would say that we invest in it and

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:16.559
we double down on it.

00:12:17.119 --> 00:12:26.719
And I like that approach because it's almost an open collaboration between teams.

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:29.919
Like how do we come up with the best ideas?

00:12:29.919 --> 00:12:32.640
How do we move on from bad ideas quickly?

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:35.280
And then how do we really hone in on what's good?

00:12:36.239 --> 00:12:37.840
And so I think it works well.

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:43.919
The hard part about it is sometimes managing a lot of things going on at once.

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:50.719
I think for anyone that codes or is in data science, they know how intense some of the

00:12:50.719 --> 00:12:52.080
projects can get.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:59.599
And so I think managing expectations and trying to communicate requirements or needs is super

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:00.080
important.

00:13:01.039 --> 00:13:07.679
But generally, if you have good ideas or you can constantly come up with new ones and find

00:13:07.679 --> 00:13:12.159
a way to really communicate them, it makes for a fun environment.

00:13:17.119 --> 00:13:21.840
Can I just ask one quick follow-up to that based on part of what you were saying?

00:13:23.440 --> 00:13:32.400
I like the idea of being able to pivot quickly and doubling down on the things that are worth

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:33.200
doubling down on.

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:38.719
Do you ever get pushback when you're dropping some of the stuff that is no longer seen as

00:13:38.719 --> 00:13:39.119
important?

00:13:39.119 --> 00:13:40.400
And how do you deal with that?

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:42.500
Yeah.

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:50.960
I mean, there's always going to be pushback from some area where there's so many people

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:59.599
to please and there's so much that is in the realm of possibilities or opportunities.

00:14:00.239 --> 00:14:06.559
And I think managing expectations and really just trying to communicate is super, super

00:14:06.559 --> 00:14:07.059
important.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:15.280
And I think that that's where sometimes you get into trouble is not communicating needs

00:14:15.280 --> 00:14:21.919
or not finding a way to really communicate so that someone else has understanding.

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:24.159
And yeah.

00:14:24.159 --> 00:14:31.760
So, I mean, the short answer is there's no perfect solution and there's always going

00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:35.119
to be someone that wants to go one way and you want the other.

00:14:35.119 --> 00:14:41.679
But the more that you can kind of be confident in what you're planning to do or want to do

00:14:41.679 --> 00:14:46.159
and then really just doing it, it makes it a lot easier to kind of come back with, well,

00:14:46.159 --> 00:14:48.880
we didn't get this done, but here's what we got done.

00:14:49.599 --> 00:14:52.960
And things like that are helpful.

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:59.039
Do you have any tips on communicating those expectations?

00:15:03.039 --> 00:15:05.520
I almost want to say, I'll let you know when I find them.

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:13.280
But I would say, you know, really just going back to kind of be, how do we explain this

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:14.960
to someone that doesn't understand it?

00:15:15.599 --> 00:15:20.559
And the best way to do that, in my opinion, is kind of treat it like you're explaining

00:15:20.559 --> 00:15:21.520
it to a six-year-old.

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:24.799
How do you explain the big picture?

00:15:25.599 --> 00:15:26.320
What's the goal?

00:15:27.119 --> 00:15:28.000
Why does it matter?

00:15:29.359 --> 00:15:30.320
What does it require?

00:15:31.359 --> 00:15:37.039
And not getting too in the weeds of the details, I guess.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:43.280
I think anytime that you approach data science, you're always going to find people that really

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:49.280
don't understand it or don't understand what's involved with the code or how it needs to

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:49.679
scale.

00:15:51.039 --> 00:15:57.440
And so the more that you can kind of bring it to a mutual understanding or common ground,

00:15:58.080 --> 00:15:59.200
that makes it easier.

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:03.520
But it's certainly a topic that I think over time will get better.

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:08.799
I think data fluency is something that will improve in the future.

00:16:08.799 --> 00:16:11.200
I think more and more people will code.

00:16:12.159 --> 00:16:13.440
I would love to see it.

00:16:14.559 --> 00:16:19.119
I guess from my perspective, I'm a self-taught coder.

00:16:19.119 --> 00:16:25.919
And so I think there's so much great material out in open source, whether that's books or

00:16:25.919 --> 00:16:29.119
videos, webinars, packages.

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:34.479
All of it really comes together to create a more open environment where that understanding

00:16:34.479 --> 00:16:35.359
starts to bridge.

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:38.000
But I think we're kind of early in the game.

00:16:38.719 --> 00:16:43.679
I think that data science is relatively new, even though it's super, super old.

00:16:44.479 --> 00:16:52.479
But the concept of how much data is becoming available and how much data is being generated

00:16:52.479 --> 00:16:56.719
really opens up that door for people to start having that conversation.

00:16:58.640 --> 00:16:59.119
Thank you.

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:04.719
Tatiana, I see you asked a question in the chat around a framework.

00:17:05.439 --> 00:17:09.119
Would you want to introduce yourself and jump in and ask that question?

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:10.400
Sure.

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:12.319
Well, first of all, thank you so much for organizing.

00:17:12.319 --> 00:17:13.359
This is great.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.640
I thank Zachary for sharing your knowledge so generously.

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:17.599
This is appreciated.

00:17:20.239 --> 00:17:22.800
I got some online certifications in data science.

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:26.319
Obviously, I'm not a super big expert in the subject, and I'm willing to learn.

00:17:26.319 --> 00:17:29.359
I'm currently working as a business intelligence analyst.

00:17:29.359 --> 00:17:33.920
And I have a question about frameworks that you use when approaching a new topic, from

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:39.040
how you manage expectations to how you decide which project, in your words, is good or bad.

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:44.079
Do you have specific APIs that you go to measure your new project against?

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:51.359
Do you have specific steps that you go from, I don't know, from deciding on whether or

00:17:51.359 --> 00:17:58.479
not to take it on to measuring which model is best to use to maybe setting adoption targets

00:17:58.479 --> 00:18:02.160
and making sure that the data is validated and the users are using it?

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:04.719
So any tips that you can give regarding that?

00:18:05.839 --> 00:18:08.000
Yeah, no, I think that that's a great question.

00:18:09.119 --> 00:18:16.319
And so I guess the way that I've approached projects has always been, and not always.

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:20.959
I wish that I had approached projects, you know, always this way.

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:22.800
But I always start with a package.

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:29.280
And the first package that I started at the Economics Institute was this package called

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:30.079
EI Tools.

00:18:30.719 --> 00:18:38.880
And it's a conglomerate of many things in the tidyverse or in use this, for anyone that's

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:39.680
familiar with that.

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:41.760
But I always start with a package.

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:47.359
So anytime I have a new idea, I build out, you know, a simple package and then store

00:18:47.359 --> 00:18:50.800
it, you know, everything that's related to that inside of that package.

00:18:51.439 --> 00:18:57.199
And I think what that offers the opportunity to do is to really have organization around

00:18:57.199 --> 00:18:58.400
all the things going on.

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:02.160
So if an idea gets dropped, it's not a big deal.

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:02.880
It's still there.

00:19:04.079 --> 00:19:10.560
But at least it's getting to the right framework or starting to be in the right form before

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:12.000
you really pursue something.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:20.319
And so I guess by way of example, when I was getting started, I built out this big application

00:19:20.319 --> 00:19:22.719
and it had a ton of functionality.

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:26.000
And it was more or less just me learning.

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:33.680
But I didn't build it in a package, you know, files were hard referenced.

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:38.719
And there was just a million things that, you know, could have been improved if I had

00:19:38.719 --> 00:19:41.439
come up with kind of that initial package structure.

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:48.959
And so I think the more that you kind of dive into projects, you start to kind of find a

00:19:48.959 --> 00:19:49.760
flow.

00:19:49.760 --> 00:19:52.319
And I think the package structure really works well for me.

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:56.319
And I would say it's not an easy thing to get through.

00:19:57.520 --> 00:19:58.800
None of it's easy.

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:07.520
And it all takes a lot of time and learning, you know, trying, failing, all things that

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:08.160
I've done.

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:15.359
And so, yeah, I would say as long as you have kind of a positive mindset about it and try

00:20:15.359 --> 00:20:18.959
to get things organized, the better off you'll be.

00:20:19.520 --> 00:20:26.479
And then in terms of, you know, model performance and how to think about all that, I think it's

00:20:26.479 --> 00:20:29.599
such a big topic that there's no perfect answer.

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:36.880
I think the more that you can focus on kind of the end output or what the value is of

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:39.280
what you're trying to do, the better.

00:20:39.280 --> 00:20:42.239
And then the rest of it is kind of just details.

00:20:42.239 --> 00:20:47.760
Thank you, Zach.

00:20:48.479 --> 00:20:53.439
I see there's a lot of chat, a conversation going on in the chat around a specific question

00:20:53.439 --> 00:20:53.760
too.

00:20:53.760 --> 00:20:57.199
So, Hugh, I'd love to have you ask your question live.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:03.040
Sure, and thank you, Septori and Bruno.

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:05.599
Those are really good thoughts, things I hadn't considered before.

00:21:07.119 --> 00:21:08.560
I'm also mostly self-taught.

00:21:08.560 --> 00:21:10.719
It's nice to hear that I'm not alone.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:16.000
But one of the things that I know I personally struggle with is every time I pick up a new

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:21.680
resource or any kind of training, I'm finding things that I feel like I should have known

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:23.920
early on or, you know, blind spots in my knowledge.

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:27.599
Do you have any strategies for kind of proactively seeking those out?

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:38.319
Yeah, so, you know, I think it's a very individual question where I think there's plenty of ways

00:21:38.319 --> 00:21:39.359
that people can learn.

00:21:40.239 --> 00:21:47.760
For me, I love books and I have too many that I haven't read, too many that I buy and I'm

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:49.599
like, I'm gonna read it and then I just don't.

00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:57.760
But what I like about books is if you start from the very top and you finish it, you have

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:00.560
so much knowledge that that author had.

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:05.599
And so a great example is just the data science for our book.

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:13.520
And it took me a long time to really get through the entire book, go through all the exercises

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:15.680
and to really understand the concepts.

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:22.000
But once I felt like I had really mastered all the concepts or really read through all

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:26.000
the chapters, I felt like I had almost a framework.

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:32.319
And same thing with the R Packages book or, you know, the Mastering Chinese book.

00:22:33.119 --> 00:22:36.560
And there's actually this book that's called The Big Book of R.

00:22:37.599 --> 00:22:44.400
And it's basically just links to books on different topics or different ideas, different

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:47.119
approaches or things that you could learn.

00:22:47.119 --> 00:22:49.280
And so I always think that that's a really great reference.

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:52.400
Videos are super helpful, at least for me.

00:22:53.599 --> 00:23:01.280
But I mean, anything, you know, training courses or, you know, in-person meetups or, and I

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:06.640
know we're kind of still in COVID, so maybe not in-person meetups, but things like this,

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:13.760
you know, how do you think about new ideas or get someone else to share ideas on code

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:18.880
or data science, modeling, you know, all of these different things that are available.

00:23:18.880 --> 00:23:26.719
So, yeah, I would say that the fear of not knowing what you should have known, that's

00:23:26.719 --> 00:23:27.520
always present.

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:29.599
Like, I know that there's a million things I don't know.

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:34.319
But I do know that there's ways to find it or to learn it.

00:23:34.319 --> 00:23:40.319
And so as long as you kind of have a learning mindset, then, you know, it's always the best

00:23:40.319 --> 00:23:40.959
place to start.

00:23:41.599 --> 00:23:41.920
Thank you.

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:43.119
I appreciate that.

00:23:43.119 --> 00:23:46.800
So your stack of unread books sounds like you're describing my nightstand.

00:23:50.239 --> 00:23:55.680
I have a coffee table, and I think sometimes when people come over and, you know, they'll

00:23:55.680 --> 00:24:00.479
see it, like right now, the book that I haven't gotten all the way through, would love to,

00:24:00.479 --> 00:24:03.760
is this book called Full Stack D3.

00:24:04.319 --> 00:24:07.199
And it's this gorgeous book, gorgeous cover.

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:10.560
And it's just this massive textbook.

00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:13.359
And I think people always come in and they're like, you're not reading this.

00:24:13.359 --> 00:24:14.719
And I'm like, yeah, no, I'm not.

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:19.920
But I'm trying to, you know, I'm trying to, so.

00:24:20.800 --> 00:24:24.479
The question is, is your nightstand and coffee table made of these books?

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:30.560
I do like woodworking.

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:35.680
So I actually built like my record stand, but how to make anything out of books.

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:37.920
That's a new idea.

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:40.400
So maybe I'll have to think about that.

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:46.239
I see there's a few helpful books that people are sharing in the chat window as well.

00:24:46.239 --> 00:24:50.719
So feel free to share any others there for anyone listening in too.

00:24:51.119 --> 00:24:53.439
There's a few anonymous questions coming in too.

00:24:53.439 --> 00:24:55.680
So I want to make sure I ask a few of those.

00:24:57.199 --> 00:25:00.000
And the first one was, how do you communicate your results?

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:04.000
Do you use the open source solution, enterprise, cloud or something else?

00:25:05.599 --> 00:25:10.079
Yeah, so I think that that's a great, a great question.

00:25:12.079 --> 00:25:18.719
So I think when you're developing on your own, you have open source to leverage and really

00:25:19.119 --> 00:25:21.839
constantly evolving technology.

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:29.920
And I think when you're in a company, the thing that I didn't understand before was really,

00:25:29.920 --> 00:25:40.400
you know, there are predetermined systems or predetermined technology solutions that you

00:25:40.400 --> 00:25:44.400
kind of have to start with where, you know, even if there's a better solution out there,

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:46.560
what's available is kind of what you get.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:54.640
And so I think there's almost this balance between what do we have access to today and

00:25:54.640 --> 00:25:57.680
what do we really want to have access to tomorrow?

00:25:59.119 --> 00:26:04.239
You know, and how do we start to communicate where these different technologies come into

00:26:04.239 --> 00:26:08.479
place or what that would enable you to do?

00:26:09.040 --> 00:26:10.959
And I think that's a really good question.

00:26:10.959 --> 00:26:13.040
Enable you to do.

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:19.359
And I think, you know, developing on your own, I would always urge people to constantly

00:26:19.359 --> 00:26:23.359
push new technologies and to find ways to really utilize them.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:31.359
And I actually, I saw this PDF where it went over the data landscape or all of the different

00:26:31.359 --> 00:26:34.000
technologies that are going on in the world.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:35.199
And there's so much.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.640
And so I think opportunity is there.

00:26:39.439 --> 00:26:45.680
And you just have to find out how do we kind of handpick what's really going to work for

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:48.079
our group or for the company?

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:50.800
And then how do we start to kind of pursue it?

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:53.760
Yeah, hopefully that helps.

00:26:56.560 --> 00:27:01.680
Following up on that question, I guess, if you like find a technology that you want to

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:07.439
pursue, what does that process look like for you or what tips you have for someone

00:27:07.439 --> 00:27:08.640
who's trying to do that?

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:10.880
Yeah, absolutely.

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:17.839
So I think that really gets to communicating with stakeholders, right?

00:27:17.839 --> 00:27:26.560
So finding some way to use what you have access to today to provide value and then coming

00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:30.719
back and saying, I know that you love this, but here's what we could do with this.

00:27:31.359 --> 00:27:39.760
And I think it's really finding ways to produce something that people really understand and

00:27:39.760 --> 00:27:46.000
view as valuable and then showing them how they, that new technologies or additional

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:52.479
systems could really enhance that or improve it, scale it, and just showing them kind of

00:27:52.479 --> 00:27:54.079
what that next step might look like.

00:27:55.280 --> 00:28:00.319
But really just opening up the conversation, finding ways to ask questions or to say,

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:03.839
here's something that I think would be super valuable.

00:28:03.839 --> 00:28:05.119
How should we approach that?

00:28:05.680 --> 00:28:11.119
Because I think that that's also something that people should be comfortable with is

00:28:11.119 --> 00:28:16.160
you're not always going to know how to do something like that or how to really start

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:17.520
asking those questions.

00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:23.359
And so I think, you know, just starting with, hey, here's something I'm thinking through.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.319
Here's why I think that might be valuable.

00:28:26.319 --> 00:28:30.079
You know, how should we think about that or how could we approach that?

00:28:30.959 --> 00:28:32.400
It's always super, super helpful.

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:35.280
Cool.

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:35.680
Thank you.

00:28:37.439 --> 00:28:42.160
Bruno, I see you had asked a question earlier around the data that Zach works with.

00:28:42.160 --> 00:28:44.400
Would you want to ask that question live?

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:46.800
Yeah, sure.

00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:47.199
Hi.

00:28:47.199 --> 00:28:47.920
Thanks for meeting.

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:52.160
I think you just muted yourself on accident.

00:28:53.359 --> 00:28:53.839
Sorry.

00:28:53.839 --> 00:28:54.239
There you go.

00:28:54.239 --> 00:28:55.760
Hi, how are you doing?

00:28:56.880 --> 00:28:58.560
Thanks for doing this.

00:28:58.560 --> 00:29:04.479
I was just wondering at the MasterCard scale, like with many data scientists, how do you

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:08.160
process everything you can use?

00:29:08.959 --> 00:29:11.119
Like you have access to so much data.

00:29:11.119 --> 00:29:13.040
Like what resources do you use?

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:17.199
What challenge do you face processing all that information?

00:29:18.079 --> 00:29:18.400
Yeah.

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:22.319
So, you know, I think that that's a great question.

00:29:23.119 --> 00:29:30.479
And when it comes to data and even just our group, so our group is made up of economists

00:29:30.479 --> 00:29:31.680
and data scientists.

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:37.760
And so even the economists look at as much data as they possibly can.

00:29:38.800 --> 00:29:45.280
We were reviewing with a vendor, you know, how many different series or how many different

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:47.760
things we look at over a given year.

00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:49.119
And it's a lot.

00:29:49.680 --> 00:29:55.760
So I think the more that you can be curious about what's available or how do we find ways

00:29:55.760 --> 00:30:02.800
to really leverage that or view it, visualize it, model it, the better off you'll be.

00:30:02.800 --> 00:30:10.239
But there's certainly plenty of challenges along the way to actually getting data, then

00:30:10.239 --> 00:30:15.199
going through a process of modeling or coming up with summary statistics.

00:30:15.199 --> 00:30:17.199
And then really what's the end output?

00:30:17.199 --> 00:30:18.479
How do we visualize that?

00:30:18.479 --> 00:30:20.079
How do we communicate it to others?

00:30:21.119 --> 00:30:25.280
And so I think the more that you constantly stay curious, the better off you are.

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:30.719
But there's certainly plenty of challenges that come up along the way.

00:30:35.359 --> 00:30:37.520
Maybe a bit related to this.

00:30:37.520 --> 00:30:42.560
There was an anonymous question that asked, have you had any issues with using large data

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:43.520
sets in R?

00:30:44.239 --> 00:30:46.640
And do you have any favorite packages to deal with that?

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:48.079
Yeah.

00:30:48.079 --> 00:30:58.479
So, you know, I think when it comes to that, R works for just about anything, at least

00:30:58.479 --> 00:30:59.280
from what I've found.

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:04.880
There are certainly times where you're trying to do too much with it and it might be slow.

00:31:04.880 --> 00:31:12.239
But generally speaking, you could load in massive files and manipulate all of it and

00:31:12.239 --> 00:31:14.880
then output it to some small table.

00:31:15.760 --> 00:31:20.959
I think that SQL is kind of the natural progression to larger and larger data.

00:31:22.239 --> 00:31:26.239
That could be, you know, a million different things, or you could view that in a million

00:31:26.239 --> 00:31:26.800
different ways.

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:34.800
But finding some way to store the data and then to pull some level of calculation without

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:38.880
pulling the full thing, that's kind of the best solution.

00:31:39.119 --> 00:31:39.920
The best solution.

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:45.280
So dbplyr is kind of the go-to, at least for me.

00:31:45.280 --> 00:31:52.880
I like writing in R more than I like writing SQL, even though I do totally value SQL and

00:31:52.880 --> 00:31:54.160
I think it's a valuable skill.

00:31:56.079 --> 00:31:59.439
I just love tidyverse and R packages.

00:32:03.199 --> 00:32:03.680
Thank you.

00:32:04.560 --> 00:32:08.959
Saul, I see you just asked a question around metrics for success.

00:32:08.959 --> 00:32:11.199
Do you want to add a little bit of context there?

00:32:16.319 --> 00:32:17.119
Or I can just ask.

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:23.040
The question is, what are metrics that Mastercard uses to measure success or impact?

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:28.400
I think that's a great question.

00:32:28.800 --> 00:32:32.719
It's something that I think about often.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:37.760
I don't know that we have a perfect solution for that.

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:46.959
You know, I think if you are generating revenue, that's a super simple way to, you know,

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:49.040
kind of measure success.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:58.560
Our group currently, you know, we are pursuing that, but when we got started, you know, that

00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:00.640
wasn't part of what we were doing.

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:06.079
And so I think that that's really when it starts to get down to, you know, how much

00:33:06.079 --> 00:33:08.479
are we communicating with clients?

00:33:08.479 --> 00:33:10.640
How much are we communicating with stakeholders?

00:33:11.199 --> 00:33:16.640
Are we helping them to do their jobs better or to have a better understanding of, you

00:33:16.640 --> 00:33:18.959
know, data or the macro view?

00:33:20.319 --> 00:33:23.680
And, you know, are we really enabling them to do better?

00:33:23.680 --> 00:33:28.640
And so I think there's plenty of opportunities to kind of measure or to try and figure out,

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:30.959
you know, how do we view this as valuable?

00:33:32.319 --> 00:33:38.000
But I think those are kind of the two avenues that I would kind of identify.

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:44.880
I know one of the examples you had shared with me was on, like, travel and sharing some

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:45.680
of those insights.

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:51.599
I guess taking that, like, success question a bit further, like, how would you measure

00:33:51.599 --> 00:33:53.040
success for that project?

00:33:54.800 --> 00:34:03.839
Yeah, so I think very early on, we kind of identified core themes.

00:34:04.079 --> 00:34:12.800
And so we started with this idea of, you know, how do we come up with, you know, six or seven

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:17.919
themes that broadly we want to cover or that we want to have a view on?

00:34:17.919 --> 00:34:20.800
And then how do we constantly kind of enhance it?

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:27.679
So if you were to look at our first projects or our first, you know, dashboards or reports,

00:34:28.639 --> 00:34:34.639
we took a view or tried to come up with a view, and then we constantly just made it better.

00:34:34.639 --> 00:34:40.719
So I don't know that we had any measure of success other than, you know, people telling

00:34:40.719 --> 00:34:44.000
us that they liked it, they valued it, you know, they appreciated it.

00:34:46.239 --> 00:34:54.000
But in terms of kind of measuring how well we're doing, I think it's certainly an area

00:34:54.080 --> 00:35:02.080
that we could probably do some more exploring or thinking through.

00:35:04.639 --> 00:35:05.040
Thank you.

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:09.120
And I just shared that link in the chat if you want to check out some of that work, too.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:12.560
Seth, I see you asked a question in the chat.

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:14.159
Can I pass the mic over to you?

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:21.120
Yeah, thanks, Zach, for sharing a lot of these insights.

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:27.919
A lot of the discussion earlier was around, like, you know, kind of coding and things

00:35:27.919 --> 00:35:28.639
of that nature.

00:35:29.919 --> 00:35:36.239
How do you, I guess, how do you ensure that, like, your team is all kind of using, is up

00:35:36.239 --> 00:35:39.600
to date, basically, like, you know, a lot of people have different varying levels of

00:35:39.600 --> 00:35:41.919
skill with regard to coding or data science.

00:35:42.479 --> 00:35:46.399
How do you guys kind of make sure that people are kind of in sync?

00:35:47.600 --> 00:35:50.000
Yeah, no, I think that that's a great question.

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:56.320
And even for, you know, data scientists, so, like, for me, I'm very code first.

00:35:57.679 --> 00:36:03.280
But a lot of people that we work with or that are part of our group, they work within Tableau.

00:36:04.399 --> 00:36:10.159
And so even with Tableau, you know, the funny thing about it is there's, and I'm probably

00:36:10.159 --> 00:36:16.320
kind of getting sidetracked with a different, maybe I'll mention that after, but there's

00:36:16.320 --> 00:36:22.399
no easy way to make sure that everyone's on the same page or has the same code or has

00:36:22.399 --> 00:36:23.840
the same understanding of code.

00:36:25.120 --> 00:36:30.239
What's worked for us is trying to figure out, you know, how do we leverage each other's

00:36:30.239 --> 00:36:33.840
skills, regardless of technologies.

00:36:34.479 --> 00:36:38.000
And, you know, a great example is really Tableau.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:44.719
So the economists will come up with these great views or these great dashboards, and

00:36:44.800 --> 00:36:51.120
then I can take those and make them into code or find ways to visualize them differently,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:53.600
put them into a public report.

00:36:54.479 --> 00:36:59.600
And so I think it's really just gets down to communication, having an understanding

00:36:59.600 --> 00:37:04.719
of skills, and then trying, you know, along the way to teach each other and to learn.

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:11.439
And so I guess the side portion that I was going to go off into was, under the hood,

00:37:11.439 --> 00:37:13.199
Tableau is XML.

00:37:13.199 --> 00:37:18.639
And so for a coder, like, I love trying to parse all of it and trying to understand,

00:37:18.639 --> 00:37:20.080
like, what can I pull out of this?

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:26.320
Or, you know, how do I pull this color palette or things that are kind of more nerdy?

00:37:27.199 --> 00:37:32.239
But it's, you know, finding ways to do what you love, even though it might not be with

00:37:32.239 --> 00:37:38.959
the tool you love or the technology, you know, it's always kind of the path that I've taken.

00:37:40.399 --> 00:37:40.899
Thanks.

00:37:41.459 --> 00:37:46.419
Expanding on that a bit further, I see there was an anonymous question that says,

00:37:46.979 --> 00:37:51.620
what are your thoughts on the no-code movement and AutoML?

00:37:53.459 --> 00:37:56.820
Yeah, so I think at the end of the day,

00:37:59.699 --> 00:38:04.419
there is value in no-code and people that don't code.

00:38:04.899 --> 00:38:14.979
I guess from my perspective, the reason why I love coding is it offers unlimited possibilities.

00:38:14.979 --> 00:38:18.820
So I think the main difference for me has always been,

00:38:20.100 --> 00:38:27.060
if this solution doesn't do what I want it to do, is there any way that I can fix that?

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:32.500
Or am I kind of set with what is available?

00:38:32.500 --> 00:38:40.100
And so for me, I love developing new things or trying to generate,

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:42.899
you know, different ways that we can do something.

00:38:42.899 --> 00:38:46.179
And so that flexibility for me has always been super important.

00:38:47.219 --> 00:38:49.780
But that being said, you know, there's a lot of value.

00:38:49.780 --> 00:38:54.659
Like, I always go to Tableau as a great example, because dragging and dropping

00:38:54.659 --> 00:38:59.540
and creating beautiful visualizations or decks, dashboards is super, super valuable.

00:38:59.939 --> 00:39:05.300
And, yeah, you know, I think both are super valuable.

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:11.540
I've just always been very code-first because I like developing and, yeah.

00:39:15.699 --> 00:39:16.340
Thanks, Zach.

00:39:17.780 --> 00:39:20.739
One other anonymous question that came in was,

00:39:20.739 --> 00:39:24.500
how do you balance your passion and personal interests

00:39:25.219 --> 00:39:28.979
and business requirements when it comes to adopting tools and projects?

00:39:30.260 --> 00:39:34.979
Yeah, you know, I think that that's another great question.

00:39:37.379 --> 00:39:38.419
It's not always easy.

00:39:39.379 --> 00:39:46.419
And, you know, you always have to find ways to have some level of balance between both.

00:39:47.620 --> 00:39:53.219
And a good example is, so when I first started, we had, you know,

00:39:53.219 --> 00:39:58.500
we had to really come up with a business plan and a way to communicate that.

00:39:58.500 --> 00:40:02.260
And we wanted to do something kind of crazy or off the wall.

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:03.620
And so we used Prezi.

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:07.379
And it was a great, you know, it was a great presentation.

00:40:07.379 --> 00:40:09.300
It was very fun. It was very interactive.

00:40:10.419 --> 00:40:14.580
And then eventually I coded, you know, an HTML presentation.

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:18.419
But I think there's always a balance of, you know,

00:40:19.060 --> 00:40:20.739
figuring out, like, what do we really need?

00:40:21.379 --> 00:40:22.820
And is this the right solution?

00:40:23.379 --> 00:40:26.979
And then at some point, the hope is always that you can really,

00:40:26.979 --> 00:40:31.219
really leverage your skills because you're starting to produce, you know,

00:40:31.219 --> 00:40:38.020
things that always can answer questions or can always satisfy some need.

00:40:38.739 --> 00:40:40.179
But that certainly takes time.

00:40:40.179 --> 00:40:43.459
And it certainly doesn't happen, you know, overnight.

00:40:43.459 --> 00:40:48.340
But the more that you have kind of your passion and your work, the better.

00:40:48.340 --> 00:40:51.620
And so I think the more that you kind of push that agenda

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:56.260
or trying to find ways to do what you love, the better off you are.

00:40:57.860 --> 00:41:03.219
Your answer and just mentioning, like, presenting the business case

00:41:03.219 --> 00:41:06.899
is making me think of something I had meant to ask earlier as well,

00:41:06.899 --> 00:41:10.500
but around the Economics Institute in general.

00:41:10.500 --> 00:41:15.540
Could you explain a bit more about what that is and how it serves as an innovation lab?

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:17.540
Yeah, absolutely.

00:41:19.219 --> 00:41:24.260
So we're really a group of, you know, economists and data scientists.

00:41:24.979 --> 00:41:32.020
And our job is to really come up with great stories and great insights.

00:41:32.580 --> 00:41:39.459
And, you know, I think that we've always taken the view of trying to view things differently,

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:44.899
trying to find the hidden story or the thing that no one else, you know, is looking at.

00:41:46.739 --> 00:41:50.659
And I think that when we look at the group as a whole,

00:41:50.659 --> 00:41:56.100
what we're really talented at is constantly being in communication with,

00:41:56.100 --> 00:42:01.060
you know, clients, stakeholders, really understanding what challenges

00:42:01.060 --> 00:42:02.979
or things that they're going through,

00:42:03.540 --> 00:42:07.300
and then finding ways to really explain what's going on.

00:42:07.300 --> 00:42:08.659
How do they think about that?

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:12.899
How do they view it or come up with new ways to approach it?

00:42:13.459 --> 00:42:20.899
And so I think, you know, the group as a whole is made up of a lot of very curious

00:42:20.899 --> 00:42:23.860
and hardworking individuals.

00:42:24.979 --> 00:42:29.540
And I think that that's really created kind of an environment where, you know,

00:42:30.260 --> 00:42:36.659
we're constantly just trying to find cool things to show or communicate.

00:42:36.659 --> 00:42:41.860
And then, you know, how do we help people to do what they do better?

00:42:41.860 --> 00:42:42.360
And so.

00:42:45.379 --> 00:42:50.260
Cool. I see Zorlu, I apologize if I'm pronouncing your name wrong,

00:42:50.260 --> 00:42:53.620
that you asked a question that follows this as well.

00:42:54.419 --> 00:42:58.899
But when you say, like, do really cool things or show cool things with data,

00:42:58.899 --> 00:43:03.060
what are some of the most interesting insights that you've gotten so far

00:43:04.179 --> 00:43:06.340
for projects you've worked on at MasterCard?

00:43:07.300 --> 00:43:07.800
Yeah.

00:43:10.580 --> 00:43:14.419
I would say it's, for the most part, it's all pretty interesting.

00:43:15.379 --> 00:43:18.899
Sometimes, you know, as a data scientist, it's hard to keep up with

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:24.820
what all of the different views are or all of the interesting insights

00:43:24.820 --> 00:43:26.340
that the group generates as a whole.

00:43:27.939 --> 00:43:31.540
I would say for me, I've always enjoyed, you know,

00:43:31.540 --> 00:43:35.459
really finding ways to visualize things.

00:43:36.179 --> 00:43:40.500
So right now I'm trying to learn D3 because I just find it so cool.

00:43:41.780 --> 00:43:43.139
And it's super difficult.

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:46.419
And it's not, you know, it's not coming easy.

00:43:46.419 --> 00:43:52.340
But, you know, I think even within Tableau, you know, we have an economist,

00:43:52.340 --> 00:43:57.300
I always look at her dashboards and I'm like, wow, this is like, this is so cool.

00:43:57.939 --> 00:44:01.699
And, you know, I think it's really just trying to

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:07.540
find things that are interesting and that you would enjoy

00:44:07.540 --> 00:44:10.979
or that you find cool and then, you know, communicating it.

00:44:12.500 --> 00:44:17.540
But I guess, like, I don't know if there's a specific example.

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:19.939
Like, I would say the small business report,

00:44:19.939 --> 00:44:21.780
there's things I find super cool in that.

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:26.580
There within the travel report, you know, there are things that I found super cool in that.

00:44:28.100 --> 00:44:30.100
But, yeah, I don't know.

00:44:30.100 --> 00:44:31.939
It's probably an answer.

00:44:31.939 --> 00:44:36.340
There's so many things that are fun or cool to look at.

00:44:37.459 --> 00:44:39.139
It's probably hard to kind of pick one.

00:44:42.020 --> 00:44:46.340
In terms of the small business report, what does that show?

00:44:46.340 --> 00:44:47.780
Or what is that?

00:44:47.780 --> 00:44:49.379
Is that a visualization that you've got?

00:44:49.620 --> 00:44:56.500
Yeah, so, you know, I think when you look at our public reports and even just,

00:44:56.500 --> 00:44:59.780
you know, I can openly talk about kind of what's under the hood.

00:44:59.780 --> 00:45:05.699
So, our public reports, for the most part, have always been built with our markdown.

00:45:06.979 --> 00:45:12.419
And I think that we try to push it to the limits of what that can do.

00:45:13.459 --> 00:45:16.899
But generally, it's a very easy framework to use.

00:45:17.219 --> 00:45:19.300
It's a very easy framework to use.

00:45:20.260 --> 00:45:22.100
You can constantly improve it.

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:28.100
And so, I think there's always this element of what it started with was really, you know,

00:45:28.100 --> 00:45:29.300
analytics stuff, right?

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:31.620
Where it's very analytics heavy.

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:39.379
There's a very, you know, kind of standard view of color where we started to transition

00:45:39.379 --> 00:45:41.860
to more elegance and design.

00:45:43.060 --> 00:45:46.580
How do we create something that people are going to find visually appealing?

00:45:47.860 --> 00:45:53.459
And so, I think that that's probably like my side gig is, you know, design.

00:45:54.100 --> 00:45:55.060
I enjoy it.

00:45:55.060 --> 00:46:02.260
And I think that, you know, we bring in a lot of visualizations that weren't built before.

00:46:03.060 --> 00:46:09.459
So, things like video or pictures or, you know, graphics that are animated.

00:46:10.179 --> 00:46:15.699
And so, I think it's just finding cool ways to show what you're trying to think through

00:46:15.699 --> 00:46:16.820
or trying to communicate.

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:22.020
But I certainly kind of love when my graphics make the end cut as well.

00:46:22.020 --> 00:46:23.139
So, yeah.

00:46:26.139 --> 00:46:26.739
Awesome.

00:46:26.739 --> 00:46:27.219
Thank you.

00:46:28.100 --> 00:46:32.419
Just scrolling through to make sure I didn't miss questions from earlier.

00:46:33.540 --> 00:46:36.260
I see Saul maybe had dropped off.

00:46:36.260 --> 00:46:42.100
But asked the question earlier on, how would you advise people to learn topics like econometrics

00:46:42.100 --> 00:46:44.659
having a limited statistics background?

00:46:46.020 --> 00:46:48.179
That's a very good question.

00:46:52.260 --> 00:46:59.300
So, what I've, you know, the one thing I've realized about economics is I thought I had

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:00.820
some level of background in it.

00:47:01.860 --> 00:47:05.780
And then you meet a bunch of smart economists and you realize you really don't know much.

00:47:06.739 --> 00:47:12.179
And so, I think at the end of the day, there's so much that you can always learn.

00:47:12.899 --> 00:47:18.659
Econometrics is not super straightforward is probably the blunt answer.

00:47:19.860 --> 00:47:22.020
It's complex.

00:47:22.020 --> 00:47:25.219
There's lots of things that need to be considered or treated for.

00:47:26.580 --> 00:47:31.379
And I think that I'm constantly learning about it or trying to understand it.

00:47:32.580 --> 00:47:39.060
But I don't know that I have any tips for here's great references or, you know, a lot

00:47:39.060 --> 00:47:44.340
of this stuff I kind of learned on the job and over time.

00:47:44.340 --> 00:47:45.620
And so, yeah.

00:47:49.379 --> 00:47:49.860
Thank you.

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:53.300
Going back to that last question a little bit.

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:58.020
I know you said you like design and it's great when sometimes your visualizations are the

00:47:58.020 --> 00:47:59.139
ones put out there.

00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:07.939
How do you kind of test design and think about like what appeals to people and what's going

00:48:07.939 --> 00:48:10.179
to maybe get catch people's attention the most?

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:21.699
Yeah, I think just trying new things is kind of the fun part about design is there's always

00:48:21.699 --> 00:48:23.540
some way that you could show it differently.

00:48:24.179 --> 00:48:30.659
And there's always a different color palette or a different font or a different size of

00:48:30.659 --> 00:48:31.459
your header.

00:48:31.459 --> 00:48:37.139
And, you know, I think all of those things kind of come together to create an output.

00:48:37.139 --> 00:48:46.020
And so the easiest way to play around with design is just kind of, I guess, like design

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:51.060
is mostly at least for, you know, web frameworks.

00:48:51.060 --> 00:48:57.780
It's just having fun with, you know, CSS and JavaScript and kind of just diving in, changing

00:48:57.780 --> 00:49:04.179
around, you know, backgrounds or like we started with very, very bold and fluorescent colors.

00:49:04.179 --> 00:49:09.379
And then we realized, well, maybe not everyone likes looking at something so, you know, intense.

00:49:09.379 --> 00:49:15.780
And, you know, how do we make that maybe a bit more easy on the eyes, I guess.

00:49:15.780 --> 00:49:21.219
And, you know, how do we change a color palette to really show what we're trying to visualize?

00:49:22.340 --> 00:49:25.540
And so I think all of those things are super fun to play around with.

00:49:26.500 --> 00:49:30.580
And yeah, just kind of getting in there and changing everything.

00:49:34.179 --> 00:49:39.939
I know you said, we've said already too, but that Brooklyn said you want this to be a place of

00:49:39.939 --> 00:49:48.100
innovation and that there's been reports that were more of static text and PDS, which you're

00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:49.139
trying to make cooler.

00:49:50.260 --> 00:49:55.379
I'm just wondering, like, is there an example of a report that you've done that for internally

00:49:55.379 --> 00:49:57.620
or what kinds of reports for those?

00:49:58.580 --> 00:49:59.060
Yeah.

00:49:59.060 --> 00:50:06.020
So, you know, I think that one of the big things that Griffin and I are always on the same page

00:50:06.020 --> 00:50:07.860
about was interactivity.

00:50:07.860 --> 00:50:16.179
So how do we increase someone's ability to really play around with it or, you know, to

00:50:16.179 --> 00:50:19.620
really understand by kind of seeing the numbers along the way.

00:50:20.899 --> 00:50:25.939
And so I think most of our reports have really been designed around that.

00:50:26.179 --> 00:50:30.820
And we try to stay away from PowerPoint unless we're presenting something kind of to the

00:50:30.820 --> 00:50:31.540
business side.

00:50:32.659 --> 00:50:36.020
We try to stay away from, you know, kind of static outputs.

00:50:37.219 --> 00:50:42.260
But that being said, you know, with our public reports, we still come out with PDS that are

00:50:42.260 --> 00:50:43.300
gorgeous as well.

00:50:44.500 --> 00:50:49.300
You know, so I think there's always that level of you're never probably going to get rid of

00:50:49.300 --> 00:50:52.419
it all and not everything can be interactive.

00:50:52.419 --> 00:50:58.659
But for the most part, we've made most of our outputs interactive, which is fun, you

00:50:58.659 --> 00:51:02.100
know, for me and I think for just the team as a whole.

00:51:04.979 --> 00:51:05.459
Cool.

00:51:05.459 --> 00:51:06.340
Thank you.

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:11.219
I'm scrolling through to make sure I haven't missed any questions right now, but just want

00:51:11.219 --> 00:51:16.020
to open up the floor to anybody if you want to jump in and ask anything live too.

00:51:16.899 --> 00:51:24.979
So in Rachel's blurb about you before the meeting, she said you're going to talk a little

00:51:24.979 --> 00:51:28.500
bit about writing a job description for tidy model engineers.

00:51:29.060 --> 00:51:30.179
I'd love to hear about it.

00:51:30.179 --> 00:51:32.979
I hate writing job descriptions and I'm writing some right now.

00:51:34.419 --> 00:51:35.379
Yeah, no.

00:51:35.379 --> 00:51:45.459
So I think even with, you know, the way that we approach titles or what we're trying to

00:51:45.540 --> 00:51:50.179
what we're trying to look for, it's very much an experiment.

00:51:51.459 --> 00:51:57.060
I think the main driving factor of that was we wanted something different that really

00:51:57.620 --> 00:51:59.620
relate to the R community.

00:52:00.419 --> 00:52:08.979
I think a lot of our code is in R currently and we're constantly trying to find ways to

00:52:09.379 --> 00:52:15.699
increase that portion of the business.

00:52:16.899 --> 00:52:24.739
So I think the main driving factor of that role is just that we wanted someone that felt

00:52:24.739 --> 00:52:30.179
that they were really talented with a specific skill to apply and to be found.

00:52:31.620 --> 00:52:36.500
I think that that's always something that you find with data science, right?

00:52:37.459 --> 00:52:41.620
You post a data science role and that could mean a billion things.

00:52:42.419 --> 00:52:46.419
And that's what's always difficult about data sciences.

00:52:46.419 --> 00:52:53.860
It covers so much that if you don't be, or if you can't find a way, that was bad English.

00:52:54.899 --> 00:53:01.780
If you can't find a way to be really specific about what you're looking for, you're probably

00:53:01.780 --> 00:53:07.699
just going to attract a lot of people, but not as many people that are focused on what

00:53:07.699 --> 00:53:10.020
you're focused on or trying to accomplish.

00:53:14.340 --> 00:53:14.899
Thanks, Zach.

00:53:15.860 --> 00:53:19.699
Is there a question that you would like to ask to the audience?

00:53:22.340 --> 00:53:25.699
I didn't prepare you for that, but I'm throwing it on you.

00:53:25.780 --> 00:53:31.780
I think that's, I mean, I just be interested like what everyone does, like what they enjoy.

00:53:32.580 --> 00:53:33.620
Do you like coding?

00:53:33.620 --> 00:53:34.739
Do you not like coding?

00:53:38.179 --> 00:53:42.020
Anyone that wants to kind of introduce themselves just on a personal level,

00:53:42.020 --> 00:53:42.979
that would be really cool.

00:53:44.500 --> 00:53:46.580
Thank you for everyone that has asked questions.

00:53:46.659 --> 00:53:52.020
I do have perhaps a related question, but I'm happy to introduce myself as well.

00:53:52.020 --> 00:53:52.820
My name is Seth.

00:53:53.620 --> 00:54:00.899
I enjoy long walks on the beach since I live in Southern California, but I am, I work for

00:54:00.899 --> 00:54:03.219
Concert AI, which is a real world data company.

00:54:03.219 --> 00:54:06.419
We work in basically cancer analytics to kind of sum it up.

00:54:08.179 --> 00:54:14.659
I'm curious because I've been a part of the data science community for a long time, but

00:54:15.620 --> 00:54:21.459
I've been a part of this wonderful little meetup for some time now, and we talk a lot

00:54:21.459 --> 00:54:25.780
about like Python and R, and those are generally our data science tools.

00:54:25.780 --> 00:54:30.899
But I'm curious, and this also could be for you, Zach, or for anybody else, is what are

00:54:30.899 --> 00:54:36.979
people's thoughts on limiting or minimizing use of both languages?

00:54:36.979 --> 00:54:42.419
So let's say you minimize Python and minimize R and just try to consolidate the team on one.

00:54:42.979 --> 00:54:49.139
My personal opinion is that there's technical debt that accrues as more languages you apply,

00:54:49.139 --> 00:54:53.300
because people obviously are comfortable in one or the other, but I'd love to hear what

00:54:53.300 --> 00:54:54.659
other people's thoughts are on that.

00:54:56.739 --> 00:55:02.100
Yeah, so I would be curious to hear everyone's thoughts as well, and maybe I'll just kind

00:55:02.100 --> 00:55:11.699
of quickly, I think it's a great question, and I'd agree that there's some level of the

00:55:11.699 --> 00:55:19.699
more technologies that you use or the more factors that you have in what makes up a data

00:55:19.699 --> 00:55:20.419
science team.

00:55:21.459 --> 00:55:27.939
Sometimes it could be hard, but I also have the sense that there's a lot of value in both

00:55:28.659 --> 00:55:33.300
or multiple, and the more that you can find ways to leverage it, the better.

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:39.300
But I think it's just a great question, so I'd be curious if anyone wants to weigh in

00:55:39.300 --> 00:55:39.620
as well.

00:55:40.580 --> 00:55:42.739
I see Brian's-

00:55:42.739 --> 00:55:43.459
I'll jump in.

00:55:44.979 --> 00:55:46.739
Hi, I'm Brian Butler.

00:55:46.739 --> 00:55:48.899
I manage the small data science team at Bennekin.

00:55:50.340 --> 00:55:51.620
I am a fan of both.

00:55:52.500 --> 00:55:56.979
In fact, my junior data scientist, before he was started with me, he was mostly R, and

00:55:56.979 --> 00:55:59.379
then he converted all to Python, and now he's doing all Python.

00:55:59.379 --> 00:56:01.540
But I'm like, these are tools.

00:56:02.340 --> 00:56:03.459
I think about a carpenter.

00:56:04.020 --> 00:56:05.300
How many nail guns do they have?

00:56:05.300 --> 00:56:07.219
How many different saws do they have?

00:56:07.219 --> 00:56:08.020
It's the same thing.

00:56:08.260 --> 00:56:13.139
If I want to bang out a quick analysis, I'm going to do it in R.

00:56:13.139 --> 00:56:17.860
I can load the data in, I can write two lines of code, and I've got a ggplot that's interactive

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:22.419
and everything else, and boom, I can solve that question pretty easily.

00:56:23.379 --> 00:56:27.459
Now, at the same time as if I'm going to do some serious natural language processing or

00:56:27.459 --> 00:56:30.979
some deep learning, I'm going to switch gears.

00:56:31.620 --> 00:56:41.459
But the best part of it is what I like doing is wrapping Python into R Markdown and presenting

00:56:41.459 --> 00:56:46.899
through these interactive apps that you can use with Plotly and R and everything else,

00:56:46.899 --> 00:56:49.300
and then you wrap the base model of Python around it.

00:56:49.300 --> 00:56:58.899
And so I just think you're not going to be skilled at every tool you use, but the more

00:56:58.899 --> 00:57:03.139
tools you have, you'll be more effective because you'll find the right one for the

00:57:03.139 --> 00:57:03.620
right job.

00:57:05.939 --> 00:57:07.060
I think that's a great answer.

00:57:10.260 --> 00:57:15.379
I see Floris and Rick are both unmuted, so I take that as raising hands.

00:57:15.939 --> 00:57:16.419
Oh, sorry.

00:57:16.419 --> 00:57:16.899
Oh, sorry.

00:57:21.699 --> 00:57:22.500
You go ahead, Floris.

00:57:23.620 --> 00:57:24.419
Oh, okay.

00:57:24.419 --> 00:57:24.899
Hello.

00:57:25.699 --> 00:57:28.500
My name is Floris Vos, I'm from the Netherlands.

00:57:29.219 --> 00:57:32.020
Actually, first time I joined this group.

00:57:32.020 --> 00:57:37.139
But I think it's a great question, and actually the same applies for packages within R, because

00:57:37.139 --> 00:57:38.580
you have so many packages.

00:57:38.580 --> 00:57:42.100
You could create a package, but you don't want to have too many packages, and you don't

00:57:42.100 --> 00:57:43.219
want to have too many packages.

00:57:43.300 --> 00:57:47.860
Because you have so many packages, you could restrict yourself to all kinds of packages.

00:57:47.860 --> 00:57:54.739
Actually, I just heard dplyr, I'm very much in front of data table, to be honest, but

00:57:54.739 --> 00:57:58.739
I use them both, and I see that both deliver a lot of value.

00:57:59.620 --> 00:58:07.459
For us, how we use it is we just have good documentation, how to use the packages, how

00:58:07.459 --> 00:58:11.939
to do your coding, so we can always take over work from each other.

00:58:11.939 --> 00:58:18.500
I think the same applies for using Python R, but even Julia or Go, if you add it to

00:58:18.500 --> 00:58:23.300
your markdown, can be used as long as you just document it well.

00:58:25.379 --> 00:58:26.340
I actually love that.

00:58:28.020 --> 00:58:34.100
Yeah, I think that documentation and having an understanding of how to use something is

00:58:35.379 --> 00:58:37.540
always something that's worth solving for.

00:58:38.419 --> 00:58:44.419
Yeah, I really like that answer, because I would love to go into an R markdown and see

00:58:44.419 --> 00:58:50.500
like 20 different languages and find ways to get value out of all of them.

00:58:51.139 --> 00:58:52.179
That'd just be kind of fun.

00:58:53.139 --> 00:58:54.659
That's why I really like that answer.

00:58:55.620 --> 00:59:01.860
Yeah, just one addition, for the whole documentation, we use actually the bookdown.

00:59:01.860 --> 00:59:04.500
Actually, the bookdown, I think it's also from...

00:59:06.100 --> 00:59:11.379
I never can pronounce his name, to be honest, but it's amazing.

00:59:11.379 --> 00:59:16.899
So we have many of those bookdowns where you just say, well, like Hadley Accurate is the

00:59:16.899 --> 00:59:18.260
R for data science.

00:59:18.260 --> 00:59:22.020
It's really great to do your documentation for your whole team, and we publish it on

00:59:22.020 --> 00:59:23.620
a web server.

00:59:23.620 --> 00:59:27.860
Easy to search for all your style guides for everything you have.

00:59:27.860 --> 00:59:28.659
Yeah, that's amazing.

00:59:29.219 --> 00:59:29.719
I like it.

00:59:32.580 --> 00:59:37.780
I would also echo the sentiment of using lots of different tools.

00:59:37.780 --> 00:59:44.580
And I'm just teaching a data science full three-month boot camp kind of course at the

00:59:44.580 --> 00:59:47.699
moment, and we just wrapped up a lot of what's going to be R, and we're going to move on

00:59:47.699 --> 00:59:48.580
to Python next week.

00:59:48.580 --> 00:59:52.179
And I told the students right from the outset that we're going to be using both R and Python.

00:59:52.179 --> 00:59:55.219
And I try to always highlight why we're doing this in R.

00:59:55.780 --> 00:59:57.300
All the statistics was in R.

00:59:57.300 --> 00:59:58.580
Data viz was all in R.

00:59:58.580 --> 00:59:59.699
Data munging was all in R.

00:59:59.699 --> 01:00:00.899
Reporting was all in R.

01:00:00.899 --> 01:00:04.419
And when we move on to Python, we'll be doing the deep learning and machine learning, things

01:00:04.419 --> 01:00:05.620
like that, inside of Python.

01:00:05.620 --> 01:00:07.699
But I'm not going to make them do statistics in Python.

01:00:08.260 --> 01:00:10.659
I don't think it's worthwhile.

01:00:10.659 --> 01:00:12.820
And I don't think it's nice to do data munging in Python either.

01:00:12.820 --> 01:00:16.260
So they have nice tools to do that also in R.

01:00:16.260 --> 01:00:20.260
So I'll show them some of it, but they're not going to be at the same level in all skills

01:00:20.260 --> 01:00:21.139
in both of them.

01:00:21.139 --> 01:00:25.939
So I like the idea of use the tools that you got and use the diversity that you got.

01:00:26.580 --> 01:00:30.820
Instead of trying to do an us versus them, no, we've got to do everything in this package

01:00:30.820 --> 01:00:32.179
or everything in this language.

01:00:32.179 --> 01:00:36.739
And everybody on that side is wrong kind of sentiment, I think, is something that I don't

01:00:36.739 --> 01:00:39.300
try to reflect in my work and give to my students either.

01:00:39.860 --> 01:00:42.899
So I like that idea of kind of using all the resources you have available to you.

01:00:42.899 --> 01:00:46.580
But when I talk to people on the ground who are not just training, but actually working

01:00:47.300 --> 01:00:52.179
in companies and consulting, they say, well, actually, what really happens is that you

01:00:52.179 --> 01:00:55.699
can use R, but the IT department is not going to support you in anything.

01:00:55.699 --> 01:00:58.580
But if you use Python, at least they'll take a look at your scripts and they make you some

01:00:58.580 --> 01:01:01.060
critique and try and help you understand what's going wrong.

01:01:01.060 --> 01:01:06.260
So the support that they get from other departments of the company also determines what they're

01:01:06.260 --> 01:01:07.620
actually going to use in the end.

01:01:07.620 --> 01:01:11.219
So there's that Paco component that is not as idealistic, I think.

01:01:11.540 --> 01:01:14.979
No, I think that that's that's accurate.

01:01:16.179 --> 01:01:21.300
I think at the end of the day, that that kind of gets back to sometimes you have systems

01:01:21.300 --> 01:01:24.340
and that's what you got to use, even if there's a better solution.

01:01:25.540 --> 01:01:30.659
And so I think that's always, you know, on the table or part of it.

01:01:31.939 --> 01:01:37.300
And I think the only way that you can get kind of people to convert or to see your side

01:01:37.300 --> 01:01:39.139
of it is just to create something cool.

01:01:39.379 --> 01:01:44.100
I think at least that's worked for me is if you can show someone something cool, then

01:01:44.100 --> 01:01:50.899
it's it's kind of easier to say, yeah, this is why I use this or yeah.

01:01:50.899 --> 01:01:58.179
And so I guess like that's the it's always part of the game.

01:01:58.179 --> 01:02:03.219
And I find that the more you can make it fun or interesting is always the easiest way to

01:02:03.219 --> 01:02:03.699
turn.

01:02:04.100 --> 01:02:05.139
Thanks for all of that.

01:02:05.139 --> 01:02:09.459
If everybody can I add context to this question?

01:02:09.459 --> 01:02:14.899
Yeah, OK, I would say thank you for asking that question and seem to fire everyone up.

01:02:14.899 --> 01:02:15.459
Yeah, I know.

01:02:15.459 --> 01:02:16.739
I should have asked it way sooner.

01:02:16.739 --> 01:02:17.300
I apologize.

01:02:18.419 --> 01:02:20.179
So the and this is great.

01:02:20.179 --> 01:02:21.620
So I don't disagree with everybody.

01:02:21.620 --> 01:02:26.020
I think that obviously all of these tools have a place in everything.

01:02:26.020 --> 01:02:31.060
So sometimes Python, especially from a data engineering perspective, can be a little bit

01:02:31.219 --> 01:02:34.179
Python, especially from a data engineering perspective.

01:02:34.179 --> 01:02:37.459
That's what people are using for for ingestion for ETL.

01:02:37.459 --> 01:02:39.540
And so it's really helpful to have that tool set.

01:02:39.540 --> 01:02:41.699
And generally, you'll always have that tool set.

01:02:41.699 --> 01:02:47.139
And for our first variety of purposes, what's interesting is what I see from like an industry

01:02:47.139 --> 01:02:52.100
perspective is that there's also a component that technical debt that you accrue when people

01:02:52.100 --> 01:02:57.379
are using multiple languages is that there are systems that need to support those languages.

01:02:57.379 --> 01:02:58.020
Right.

01:02:58.100 --> 01:03:01.699
So as Rick pointed, sometimes it's Python and that's what they're supporting.

01:03:01.699 --> 01:03:02.020
Right.

01:03:02.020 --> 01:03:03.540
Sometimes it's R, sometimes it's both.

01:03:03.540 --> 01:03:08.260
But when you have more systems or languages you need to support, there's more libraries,

01:03:08.260 --> 01:03:09.379
there's more whatever.

01:03:09.379 --> 01:03:14.260
All of that plays a technical debt on whatever the IT system, whatever the platform system.

01:03:14.260 --> 01:03:16.899
So generally, you don't want to have 20 languages.

01:03:16.899 --> 01:03:17.699
You want to limit it.

01:03:17.699 --> 01:03:19.379
And so Python and R is fine.

01:03:20.100 --> 01:03:25.860
But there's also a technical debt towards expertise, towards like if I'm if I only know

01:03:25.860 --> 01:03:30.659
how to do it in SQL and I only do it in SQL, but another team is doing it in Python and

01:03:30.659 --> 01:03:34.659
another team is doing it in R, right, you now have three different ways that you're

01:03:34.659 --> 01:03:36.739
approaching perhaps the same problem.

01:03:36.739 --> 01:03:40.179
And people only want to then deal with it in the language that they're most familiar

01:03:40.179 --> 01:03:40.899
with.

01:03:40.899 --> 01:03:46.260
And so from a broader perspective, when you're trying to scale, like it might be helpful

01:03:46.260 --> 01:03:52.100
to say, look, I know you know how to do it in SQL, but learning it in R or doing it in

01:03:52.100 --> 01:03:56.659
Python or whatever the choice would be, may have value for the company as it scales,

01:03:56.659 --> 01:04:00.899
because once that person leaves or if they go on vacation or something, someone else

01:04:00.899 --> 01:04:02.340
can then pick it up.

01:04:02.340 --> 01:04:06.260
And I think Flora said documenting it appropriately is great.

01:04:06.260 --> 01:04:07.540
And I 100% agree.

01:04:07.540 --> 01:04:09.780
But I guess that's just the context behind the question.

01:04:09.780 --> 01:04:12.739
I'm not trying to say that we should pick one language or another.

01:04:12.739 --> 01:04:14.739
But I guess, you know.

01:04:15.459 --> 01:04:17.939
Maybe if I can jump in on one quick comment about that.

01:04:17.939 --> 01:04:22.179
One of the things that I noticed, we were writing the book this past year, the R and

01:04:22.179 --> 01:04:24.260
Python for Modern Data Science.

01:04:24.260 --> 01:04:28.739
And we kind of almost had a hard time finding nice use cases.

01:04:28.739 --> 01:04:31.139
And I got some examples from colleagues on Twitter.

01:04:31.139 --> 01:04:35.780
But I realized that, you know, we organized the book in terms of you choose R or Python

01:04:35.780 --> 01:04:38.739
dependent on the type of data that you're working on.

01:04:38.739 --> 01:04:45.939
So if it's time series or unstructured or geospatial, there's different package ecosystems

01:04:45.939 --> 01:04:47.860
that are well suited in each of the languages.

01:04:47.860 --> 01:04:49.699
And some of them are better than others.

01:04:49.699 --> 01:04:51.780
Like spaCy is fantastic for NLP.

01:04:51.780 --> 01:04:55.939
I wouldn't necessarily recommend, although there's fantastic things for NLP in R, but

01:04:55.939 --> 01:04:59.780
spaCy is really kind of dominating that scene in Python.

01:04:59.780 --> 01:05:04.580
And so we kind of said, you know, think about the data structure, the format of the data,

01:05:04.580 --> 01:05:08.020
and the kind of research problem that you're dealing with.

01:05:08.020 --> 01:05:12.899
And then in the case study, we were kind of struggling to find a really nice flow, like

01:05:12.899 --> 01:05:13.939
really nice example.

01:05:13.939 --> 01:05:15.620
And we got something really nice at the end, I think.

01:05:15.620 --> 01:05:20.419
But it also occurred to me that one of the reasons people end up using R and Python that

01:05:20.419 --> 01:05:24.260
I see actually in reality with my students that are working in research is that they

01:05:24.260 --> 01:05:29.699
come into a laboratory and they inherit a really terrible Python script that they cannot

01:05:29.699 --> 01:05:32.179
make heads or tails out of it, but the thing works.

01:05:32.179 --> 01:05:34.580
And there's no reason to reinvent the wheel.

01:05:34.580 --> 01:05:38.739
But they want to wrap it in R because they can modify and do things with it and expand

01:05:38.739 --> 01:05:39.219
it in R.

01:05:39.219 --> 01:05:43.620
So instead of learning, and these are like crazy long and super complicated scripts that

01:05:43.620 --> 01:05:48.260
I guarantee are much, much easier in R, but they don't have the time to translate that

01:05:48.260 --> 01:05:48.739
all to R.

01:05:48.739 --> 01:05:51.780
So they stick with it, and then they just kind of have to deal with a Python script.

01:05:51.780 --> 01:05:56.500
So I think sometimes people use R and Python, not because idealistic reasons, not because

01:05:56.500 --> 01:05:58.820
they don't want to, but because they're stuck with it.

01:05:58.820 --> 01:06:02.979
Like they have to use this Python script or this R script because somebody wrote it and

01:06:02.979 --> 01:06:03.939
dumped it on their shoulders.

01:06:04.340 --> 01:06:05.860
100%, that's accurate.

01:06:07.060 --> 01:06:14.899
Yeah, and I was just going to say, you know, I think it's a super interesting question

01:06:14.899 --> 01:06:26.020
because it's super applicable and at every step of scale, that complexity or that ease

01:06:26.020 --> 01:06:27.379
has to be kind of addressed.

01:06:27.379 --> 01:06:32.020
And so it's almost like we know that that's a topic.

01:06:32.020 --> 01:06:33.540
We know that people are going to use both.

01:06:34.179 --> 01:06:36.739
How do we really prepare for that or address it?

01:06:36.739 --> 01:06:42.419
And I think like RStudio probably has the best answer for it, or they're working on

01:06:42.419 --> 01:06:43.939
it, one of the two.

01:06:43.939 --> 01:06:53.139
But I think that it's certainly possible that you're building without that full circle view

01:06:53.139 --> 01:06:53.860
of it, right?

01:06:53.860 --> 01:07:00.340
Like I know that there's a lot of people developing Python that I don't know and probably

01:07:00.340 --> 01:07:01.139
vice versa.

01:07:02.820 --> 01:07:07.459
And so, yeah, it's hard to have kind of a perfect solution for all of it, but I think

01:07:07.459 --> 01:07:08.659
it's an interesting question.

01:07:09.780 --> 01:07:16.899
One thing that I found really useful was that I have not restricted languages on my teams

01:07:16.899 --> 01:07:21.540
and I see certain people, because of their backgrounds, they were either more comfortable

01:07:21.540 --> 01:07:27.219
with one or the other, which was nice because it allowed for a lot of cross-training.

01:07:27.219 --> 01:07:32.820
But then if people were unsure about a problem, there were even more ways to try to come to

01:07:32.820 --> 01:07:39.060
an answer and understanding from a different approach, whether it Python or R or different

01:07:39.060 --> 01:07:45.540
packages, was really good and thought-provoking and found more errors and got better answers

01:07:45.540 --> 01:07:45.939
in the end.

01:07:47.620 --> 01:07:55.139
There is definitely stress from having more languages, but I think it's worth it.

01:07:56.020 --> 01:07:56.739
I like that.

01:07:56.739 --> 01:08:04.340
Yeah, and I think, like, the one thing that you just said was, you know, there's almost

01:08:04.340 --> 01:08:05.699
some stress from that.

01:08:05.699 --> 01:08:12.020
And I think Seth asked an earlier question about, you know, how do people stay up to

01:08:12.020 --> 01:08:13.780
date on languages?

01:08:13.780 --> 01:08:21.299
And so I think that that's one of the hard things as well, is like, if you're constantly

01:08:21.939 --> 01:08:27.220
doing something other than that, how do you stay up to date on what's going on or what's

01:08:27.220 --> 01:08:27.700
important?

01:08:28.500 --> 01:08:31.379
But I love that there's multiple ways to answer that.

01:08:31.379 --> 01:08:36.740
And like, it offers more capabilities to do that, because that's really, really valuable.

01:08:36.740 --> 01:08:38.500
And so I think that that's awesome.

01:08:42.979 --> 01:08:44.259
Yeah, all good conversation.

01:08:44.259 --> 01:08:45.220
Hi, this is Bala.

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:46.899
I just want to add one thing, Seth.

01:08:46.899 --> 01:08:54.580
So right now, if you restrict, so both Python and R right now has so much maturity and it's

01:08:54.580 --> 01:08:55.220
open source, right?

01:08:55.220 --> 01:08:58.419
A lot of packages are being, you know, contributed.

01:08:59.379 --> 01:09:05.299
For most of the standard use cases, you get packages which are wrapper around the package

01:09:05.299 --> 01:09:06.580
which is done in Python.

01:09:06.580 --> 01:09:13.459
So if there is a spaCy package for NLP in Python, there is a spaCy R, which is a wrapper

01:09:13.459 --> 01:09:17.459
which basically runs the same package in the R environment.

01:09:17.459 --> 01:09:24.580
So if it is a generic use case, which, you know, is being used across multiple industries,

01:09:24.580 --> 01:09:26.500
then you really don't have that problem.

01:09:26.500 --> 01:09:34.259
Like, oh, my developer have, it's much easier to migrate because the speed to market is

01:09:34.259 --> 01:09:38.899
what you, as a data scientist, you would like, as a data team, you would like to do.

01:09:38.899 --> 01:09:42.979
So a problem is given, you want to solve it as quick as possible.

01:09:42.979 --> 01:09:49.140
And if you're taking, or if you're adding red tape saying like, oh, you can't use Python

01:09:49.140 --> 01:09:53.220
or you can't use R, you're naturally, you know, creating blockheads.

01:09:53.220 --> 01:09:59.140
So I would say you should allow your team to explore in whichever language which is

01:09:59.140 --> 01:10:00.660
comfortable for them.

01:10:00.660 --> 01:10:04.660
But again, when they design, just think about like, are there wrappers?

01:10:04.660 --> 01:10:10.819
Can I integrate, you know, whatever I've done so that it is future proofed?

01:10:10.819 --> 01:10:11.540
Just in case.

01:10:12.979 --> 01:10:13.220
Yeah.

01:10:13.220 --> 01:10:14.979
And to be clear, I don't have any restrictions.

01:10:14.979 --> 01:10:20.259
I thought it was an interesting thought experiment before everyone spears me and cancels me or

01:10:20.259 --> 01:10:21.140
whatever.

01:10:21.140 --> 01:10:22.020
But yeah.

